In order to test the accuracy of the pairwise model (5) and to illustrate the role played by the distribution of infectious period, we consider the examples of outbreaks of several diseases mentioned in Table 1 in a population that is initially fully susceptible. We concentrate on two common and fairly simple network structures, namely homogeneous and Erdős–Rényi networks (Newman 2010), with stochastic simulations being performed using a Gillespie algorithm (Gillespie 1977; Chen and Bokka 2005). We restrict our attention to these network types as we have a homogeneous pairwise model and we would not expect it to work well for other networks. Following the derivation of the pairwise model, the per-link transmission rate is taken to be \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
